<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- Phrase 1 (mm. 1-4): C major — bright I-vii°-I opening, quarter-note motion.
  All voices move with the melody beat by beat. RH in 3rds/4ths, LH in open 5ths
  and root-position triads. IV-V-I bassline highlights the plagal flavor.
- Phrase 2 (mm. 5-8): Minor turn through Am, Em(iii), Dm(ii). G# and F# are
  chromatic passing tones in melody only — harp stays on diatonic triads.
  Em substitutes for E major (iii for non-diatonic III). Dm substitutes for D major.
  RH uses quartal voicing at Em (E4-B4 = P5) for an open, ambiguous sound.
- Phrase 3 (mm. 9-12): Return to C major at full texture. LH builds to 4-note
  F2-C3-F3-A3 and C3-G3-C4-E4. RH reaches C5-E5-G5 at final measure for high
  triumphant close. IV→I voice leading in both hands simultaneously.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- Bass line trace phrase 1: C→B→C→F→C→A→G→C (I-vii°-I-IV-I-vi-V-I arc).
- Minor section (mm. 5-8): A-E-D-G bass = vi-iii-ii-V passing through natural minor.
- Inner RH voice descends step by step: C5→B4→A4→G4→A4 in mm. 1-4.
- No parallel 5ths or octaves between RH and LH confirmed across all measures.
- C major: no accid.ges needed on key-sig notes. Chromatic melody notes
  (G#, F#) carry explicit accid="s" and are NOT doubled in RH or LH.

TEXTURE ARC:
- mm. 1-4: 2-3 note hands, energetic quarter-note motion — festive and bright
- mm. 5-8: Darker minor color, half-note suspensions, 3-note LH — introspective
- mm. 9-10: Build back to IV-I with growing LH (3→4 notes)
- mm. 11-12: Full 4-note LH both hands, RH reaches high triad at C5-E5 — joyful climax
-->
